    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{y}{y-4}} = {5} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{5\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{y-4}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{y}{y-4}} \amp = {5} \\
   {\frac{y}{y-4}} \cdot ({y-4}) \amp = {5} \cdot ({y-4}) \\
   y \amp = 5y - 20 \\
   y \mathbf{-5y} \amp = 5y - 20 \mathbf{-5y} \\
   -4y \amp = -20 \\
   \frac{-4y}{-4} \amp = \frac{-20}{-4} \\
   y \amp = 5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>y - 4 \ne 0</m>, or <m>y \ne 4</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>y = 5</m>.</p>
</solution>
